,"1240":"1240","1284":"1284","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1258":"1258","1235":"1235","1268":"1268","1453":"1453","1288":"1288","about 1284":"omkring 1284","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","England":"England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1262–":"1262–Overleden","1262–Female":"1262–Overleden","1264–Female":"1264–Overleden","1268–1288":"1268–1288","1258–1349":"1258–1349","1284–Male":"1284–Overleden","1235–1316":"1235–1316","1240–Female":"1240–Overleden","about 1293":"circa 1293","1264":"1264","1262":"1262","1240":"1240","1284":"1284","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1258":"1258","1235":"1235","1268":"1268","1453":"1453","1288":"1288","about 1284":"circa 1284","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","England":"England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1262–":"1262–Deceased","1262–Female":"1262–Deceased","1264–Female":"1264–Deceased","1268–1288":"1268–1288","1258–1349":"1258–1349","1284–Male":"1284–Deceased","1235–1316":"1235–1316","1240–Female":"1240–Deceased","about 1293":"about 1293","1264":"1264","1262":"1262","1240":"1240","1284":"1284","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1258":"1258","1235":"1235","1268":"1268","1453":"1453","1288":"1288","about 1284":"about 1284","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","England":"England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chartney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Limerick): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hAthairne</b>, a personal name based on <i>athair</i> ‘father’, originally of three syllables. The English <i>t</i> is intrusive and the surname was earlier Anglicized as   Harney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Harney","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hAthairne</b> ‘descendant of <i>Athairne</i>’, a personal name based on <i>athair</i> ‘father’, originally of three syllables and borne by a famous Old Irish satirist. The surname was sometimes also Anglicized as   Hartney  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":28,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":53,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":66,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":75,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Chartney was born in 1262, in England, her father, Richard de Chartney, was 27 and her